WEBVTT

00:06.792 --> 00:07.917
♪ (DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

00:08.125 --> 00:09.583
(STOCK EXCHANGE BELL RINGS)

00:10.250 --> 00:11.291
(CROWD ROARS)

00:14.250 --> 00:16.375
We were a few days away
from the ATMs not working.

00:17.083 --> 00:19.000
Suddenly,
folks are getting wiped out.

00:19.834 --> 00:21.792
GEORGE W. BUSH: I asked, "Are we
headed for a Great Depression?"

00:21.875 --> 00:24.625
And Bernanke said,
"You know, it looks that way."

00:25.250 --> 00:29.000
I'd look into the abyss
and I would see food lines,

00:29.583 --> 00:31.917
millions of people unemployed.

00:32.000 --> 00:34.667
Hank had just thrown up
into a waste basket.

00:34.750 --> 00:36.333
I don't know
if it was a panic attack,

00:36.417 --> 00:38.250
but the market was so fragile...

00:39.583 --> 00:41.291
We were never going
to let it get known.

00:42.250 --> 00:43.667
BUSH: John called
a press conference, said,

00:43.750 --> 00:45.417
"I'm demanding the president
have a meeting."

00:45.500 --> 00:46.917
It was high-stakes drama.

00:48.250 --> 00:52.250
The meeting sorta descended
into a little bit of chaos.

00:53.250 --> 00:56.333
Barney Frank started shouting,
"Where's your plan, McCain?"

00:56.709 --> 00:57.834
At that point, it was dire.

00:57.917 --> 00:59.291
Congress can't get it together.

00:59.625 --> 01:00.792
HENRY PAULSON: There was fear

01:00.875 --> 01:02.625
and we did it
without a playbook.

01:03.291 --> 01:04.875
The fact that
the American public hates

01:04.959 --> 01:06.792
what we did is not surprising,

01:06.875 --> 01:08.750
because in many ways,
it's un-American.

01:09.583 --> 01:11.458
♪ (MUSIC CONTINUES) ♪

01:27.333 --> 01:29.166
♪ ♪

01:29.250 --> 01:33.208
Shane Smith:
This week on  Vice:
how to survive the apocalypse.

01:34.709 --> 01:38.041
Robert Vicino:
There is no safe place
on the planet.

01:38.125 --> 01:40.125
But there are safer places.

01:40.208 --> 01:42.917
Thomas Morton:
Do you ever look forward to,
not the events leading

01:43.000 --> 01:44.500
to a situation where
you're locked in,

01:44.583 --> 01:47.250
-but the idea of being
locked in?
-No.

01:47.333 --> 01:50.792
Smith:
And then, the obsession
with light skin in Bollywood.

01:50.875 --> 01:52.417
(cheering)

01:52.500 --> 01:54.875
Gianna Toboni:
I can't help but notice
usually the main actors

01:54.959 --> 01:56.417
are fairer-skinned.

01:56.500 --> 01:58.166
You think I'm fair?

01:58.542 --> 02:01.000
(woman speaking
foreign language)

02:02.959 --> 02:06.000
(theme song playing)

02:07.625 --> 02:09.041
(crowd shouting)

02:09.125 --> 02:11.542
They're saying that right now,
it's time for change.

02:12.750 --> 02:15.375
(indistinct shouting)

02:26.542 --> 02:30.208
Doomsday preppers used to come
from the fringes of society.

02:30.291 --> 02:34.041
Since 9/11, however,
planning for a world-ending
disaster

02:34.125 --> 02:35.792
has become more and more
mainstream.

02:35.875 --> 02:39.083
Newsman:
Sales of doomsday bunkers,
fallout tents,

02:39.166 --> 02:42.125
and underground shelters are
soaring in the United States.

02:42.208 --> 02:45.291
Smith:
Today's radical changes
in the geo-political landscap,

02:45.375 --> 02:48.875
increased forced migration,
and extreme climate events,

02:48.959 --> 02:52.333
have only intensified the
country's collective anxiety.

02:52.417 --> 02:54.834
In response, new businesses
have sprung up

02:54.917 --> 02:56.500
to provide survival options

02:56.583 --> 02:59.709
for the impending collapse
of civilization.

02:59.792 --> 03:02.834
So we sent Thomas Morton
to check out what's for sale

03:02.917 --> 03:05.417
in the American
survivalist industry.

03:13.250 --> 03:15.500
Newswoman:
After a ballistic missile
launch in November,

03:15.583 --> 03:19.208
Kim Jong-un now claims
his nuclear weapons
program is complete.

03:20.041 --> 03:21.458
(sirens wailing)

03:21.542 --> 03:23.500
Newsman:
This scene follows last
night's alt-right protest

03:23.583 --> 03:25.792
with hundreds marching
at the University of Virginia

03:25.875 --> 03:27.500
while waving tiki torches.

03:28.208 --> 03:31.834
Newsman 2:
Fifty-eight people now dead,
more than 500 people wounded

03:31.917 --> 03:33.041
in a horrific shooting.

03:33.125 --> 03:34.500
There'll be more
dark days to come

03:34.583 --> 03:36.583
for so many people
who've lost everything.

03:36.667 --> 03:38.792
♪ ♪

03:39.834 --> 03:41.709
Hi, it's Thomas.

03:41.792 --> 03:43.667
It's 9/11.
I'm on Wall Street.

03:44.792 --> 03:48.417
Fortunately not that 9/11,
but in this crazy day of
climate change,

03:48.500 --> 03:51.959
wealth inequality, civil unrest,
things could happen any moment.

03:52.041 --> 03:53.667
(chorus singing)

03:53.750 --> 03:56.458
(Morton speaking)

04:15.667 --> 04:17.500
♪ ♪

04:19.500 --> 04:23.375
You got that tide,
so stay away from the--
No, keep the gas off.

04:23.458 --> 04:25.500
♪ ♪

04:27.834 --> 04:29.875
-Chris Dowhie:
The city's on fire.
-Morton: Exactly.

04:29.959 --> 04:31.375
Dowhie:
The wheel is off the bus.

04:31.458 --> 04:33.166
♪ ♪

04:36.417 --> 04:38.458
Morton:
The speedboat I'm currently
taking across the Hudson

04:38.542 --> 04:40.750
at 50 knots belongs
to Plan B Marine,

04:40.834 --> 04:42.750
a company that keeps
a fleet of similar craft

04:42.834 --> 04:44.917
docked around Manhattan,
fueled up and ready to go.

04:45.000 --> 04:48.542
Its clients pay up to $6,000
a month to lease their own
personal boats,

04:48.625 --> 04:50.250
so they can escape the island
with a quickness

04:50.333 --> 04:52.125
should the proverbial shit
go down...

04:52.208 --> 04:54.834
or hit the fan
or just happen.

04:54.917 --> 04:57.583
-Dowhie: Watch out for
this wave. It's gonna be big.
-Morton: Yeah.

04:57.667 --> 05:00.792
You're gonna want to pull back.
Pull your throttle back.

05:00.875 --> 05:02.792
Morton:
Oh, sorry. I did that
exactly wrong.

05:02.875 --> 05:05.041
-Dowhie: Yeah.
-Morton: Yeah.

05:06.875 --> 05:08.542
Morton:
So the emergencies
you're planning for

05:08.625 --> 05:10.709
aren't necessarily
nuclear apocalypse.

05:10.792 --> 05:12.792
No. We're really against
that whole theory

05:12.875 --> 05:16.291
of the zombie apocalypse
and preppers.

05:16.375 --> 05:18.125
We're an insurance policy.

05:18.208 --> 05:20.250
Why do most
of the clients
who call you,

05:20.333 --> 05:22.375
why are they looking
for this service?

05:22.458 --> 05:26.208
Some people, it's fear.
They're afraid of something
happening.

05:26.291 --> 05:28.500
It all relates back
to September 11th.

05:28.583 --> 05:30.291
If something like that
could happen,

05:30.375 --> 05:32.583
-something just as bad
could happen.
-Yeah.

05:32.667 --> 05:35.750
And they don't want to be
in that position where
they feel helpless.

05:35.834 --> 05:37.417
Morton:
I remember, like,
during the blackout--

05:37.500 --> 05:39.500
The blackout was
the biggest problem.

05:39.583 --> 05:41.625
-Everyone comes out
of the subway.
-Morton: Yeah.

05:41.709 --> 05:44.792
Dowhie:
All the lights are out
so now cars don't move,

05:44.875 --> 05:46.542
and the whole city's
in gridlock.

05:46.625 --> 05:50.667
It's an eye-opener when I speak
to some security people.

05:50.750 --> 05:54.000
What they're worried about
was something I never even
thought of.

05:54.083 --> 05:55.750
Do you take that
with a grain of salt,

05:55.834 --> 05:57.375
-when you talk to police?
-Dowhie: I do. I do,

05:57.458 --> 05:59.917
-but I'm an optimist, so...
-Morton: Yeah.

06:00.000 --> 06:02.250
-An interesting market
to be in as an optimist.
-I know, I...

06:02.333 --> 06:05.667
It's a service I provide
for other people,
not myself.

06:05.750 --> 06:06.959
No?

06:07.041 --> 06:10.208
But maybe my head
is in the sand,
like other people.

06:10.291 --> 06:13.834
'Cause things happen,
and things have happened
in the past.

06:13.917 --> 06:15.667
(indistinct radio transmission)

06:15.750 --> 06:18.542
Once you've gotten
out of the city, though,

06:18.625 --> 06:21.959
the next question is,
where do you go from there?

06:22.792 --> 06:25.041
(mooing)

06:25.125 --> 06:26.834
♪ ♪

06:26.917 --> 06:34.125
♪ I don't want
to set the world on fire ♪

06:37.625 --> 06:39.583
If you're not looking
to leave the United States,

06:39.667 --> 06:42.667
but are looking to leave
the main trouble centers,

06:42.750 --> 06:44.458
which is basically anywhere
where a lot of people live,

06:44.542 --> 06:46.834
you can come out to one
of the less populated districts,

06:46.917 --> 06:48.375
like here in South Dakota.

06:48.458 --> 06:50.875
On our way to, uh,
essentially a, kind of like,

06:50.959 --> 06:54.417
condominium complex of shelters
called Vivos xPoint.

06:54.500 --> 06:57.000
♪ ♪

06:59.417 --> 07:01.083
Morton:
Shoes off?

07:01.166 --> 07:02.917
Vicino:
Yeah, we like
to take shoes off.

07:03.000 --> 07:05.375
Keep the floors
nice and clean.

07:05.458 --> 07:08.417
-Vicino: What do you think?
-This is... This is swank.

07:08.500 --> 07:11.166
Vicino:
So this shelter
was recently completed.

07:11.250 --> 07:14.667
We built it as a showroom
for people to come,
walk through, touch and feel,

07:14.750 --> 07:16.417
and see how to do it.

07:16.500 --> 07:19.417
You know, the way
this works is they come
and they go,

07:19.500 --> 07:21.583
and they build out
their bunker over time,

07:21.667 --> 07:23.917
and everybody's got different
ideas and different plans,

07:24.000 --> 07:25.542
and that's fine.
We like that.

07:25.625 --> 07:29.083
Vicino:
But this one sold
for $150,000.

07:29.166 --> 07:34.083
Just for the improvements,
plus the shelter at 25,000,
so 175.

07:34.166 --> 07:36.375
And if you build
it out yourself,
it'd be about 50.

07:36.458 --> 07:38.542
You know, that's...
that's very reasonable.

07:38.625 --> 07:42.166
What do you get for
50,000 in the form
of a condo,

07:42.250 --> 07:44.625
or a cabin in the woods,
or whatever? Not much.

07:44.709 --> 07:46.625
Morton:
Do you feel
a sense of urgency

07:46.709 --> 07:48.041
with getting all these
things done?

07:48.125 --> 07:49.792
Or do you feel
like right now...

07:49.875 --> 07:52.125
Yes. And it's
a big discussion.

07:52.208 --> 07:54.458
-We're all having it
yesterday.
-Yeah.

07:54.542 --> 07:58.458
All I can say is,
as a company, Vivos,
we're doing the best we can,

07:58.542 --> 08:01.125
-as fast as we can,
for as long as we can.
-Yeah.

08:01.208 --> 08:04.792
To build as many shelters
to protect as many people
as possible.

08:04.875 --> 08:06.875
♪ ♪

08:08.375 --> 08:11.875
Tour guide:
Check out the incredible
entertainment room

08:11.959 --> 08:13.917
we have here for you guys.

08:14.000 --> 08:17.959
Incredible what you can do
with a bunker.

08:18.041 --> 08:20.834
Morton:
Vivos may market its shelters
to middle-class preppers,

08:20.917 --> 08:24.583
as evidenced by IKEA-
meets-CB2 furnishings
of their show bunker,

08:24.667 --> 08:28.041
but an entire cottage industry
has sprung up selling
survival skills and resources

08:28.125 --> 08:31.625
to the sweetest demographic
of all: the one percent.

08:38.750 --> 08:40.250
Do it.

08:45.000 --> 08:46.375
Morton:
Dan Clark was a bodyguard

08:46.458 --> 08:48.250
for some of the corporate
world's richest figures

08:48.333 --> 08:49.834
before starting
Clark International,

08:49.917 --> 08:51.834
a security firm in Omaha,
Nebraska, that teaches

08:51.917 --> 08:55.083
executives, famous actors,
and other high net worth
individuals,

08:55.166 --> 08:59.083
how to protect themselves
and get away from kidnappers,
terrorists, assassins,

08:59.166 --> 09:03.041
and mobs of angry low
to no net worth individuals.

09:03.125 --> 09:05.583
Being in the position
that you're in,
you may find yourself

09:05.667 --> 09:07.750
where you actually
have to defend yourself.

09:07.834 --> 09:10.792
And there's some
fundamentals of self-defense
that you should know

09:10.875 --> 09:12.500
and that we're gonna
practice today.

09:12.583 --> 09:15.542
Front foot's gonna go forward,
back foot's gonna follow.

09:15.625 --> 09:17.792
Just like that.
That's really good, Thomas.
Good.

09:17.875 --> 09:20.041
The people of high net worth,

09:20.125 --> 09:24.583
not only do they have
the regular concerns
as the average citizen,

09:24.667 --> 09:28.417
of the random crime,
or run across
the mentally ill,

09:28.500 --> 09:31.041
but the people of real
high net worth,

09:31.125 --> 09:34.583
they need to concerned,
as well, as far as
targeted crime.

09:34.667 --> 09:38.333
-Morton: Whoa, whoa.
-(men shouting indistinctly)

09:39.875 --> 09:41.458
Morton:
In recent years,
have you noticed,

09:41.542 --> 09:45.625
has there been an uptick
in people coming to you
for service?

09:45.709 --> 09:47.250
Yes. Absolutely so.

09:47.333 --> 09:49.917
I think it's a combination
of several factors.

09:50.000 --> 09:52.208
I think it's a combination
of terrorism.

09:52.291 --> 09:55.583
I think it's a combination
of potentially being targeted.

09:55.667 --> 09:57.500
-(screeching)
-That's it.

09:57.583 --> 10:01.625
In addition to a little bit
of the political unrest
that's going on right now.

10:01.709 --> 10:05.041
From here, I'm exploding.
Boom, boom-boom. Like that.

10:05.125 --> 10:07.250
-And then,
I'm coming back online.
-Morton: Yeah.

10:07.333 --> 10:10.417
-And when you get good enough,
you make your own sound effects.
-Morton: Okay. (laughs)

10:10.500 --> 10:12.291
Morton:
Part of Clark International's
business model

10:12.375 --> 10:14.959
is keeping their
roster of clients
confidential.

10:15.041 --> 10:16.917
-Clark: That's
very good, Thomas.
-Okay.

10:17.000 --> 10:18.917
Morton:
Which is always a selling poit
to the have-mores in society,

10:19.000 --> 10:21.250
who like to keep their private
lives as private as possible.

10:21.333 --> 10:24.250
Especially things like
what they own and
what they're afraid of.

10:24.333 --> 10:27.375
To wit, there's purportedly
an entire scene of
tech billionaires

10:27.458 --> 10:28.917
within the prepping
community

10:29.000 --> 10:30.417
who've been buying up
bolt-hole properties

10:30.500 --> 10:32.000
in New Zealand
and elsewhere.

10:32.083 --> 10:34.458
And which purportedly includes
the likes of Peter Thiel,

10:34.542 --> 10:38.542
LinkedIn founder Reid Hoffman,
Reddit founder Steve Huffman.

10:38.625 --> 10:40.250
Guys it's safe to say
are no dummies,

10:40.333 --> 10:42.458
especially when
it comes to what they do
with their capital.

10:42.542 --> 10:45.208
At least one tech tycoon,
however, is spending his
time and money

10:45.291 --> 10:47.917
trying to raise the alarm
about the economic catastrophe

10:48.000 --> 10:49.834
looming in our
wealth-disparity gap,

10:49.917 --> 10:52.834
instead of just preparing
to run for the hills
in his new Tesla.

10:52.917 --> 10:55.208
Intuition about the future

10:55.291 --> 10:58.458
is the essence of good
entrepreneurship.

10:58.542 --> 11:02.709
So what do I see
in our future today,
you ask?

11:02.792 --> 11:04.375
I see pitchforks,

11:04.458 --> 11:08.875
as in angry mobs
with pitchforks.

11:10.709 --> 11:12.500
I love these mugs
by the way.

11:12.583 --> 11:14.458
-You like our trickle-down mugs?
-Oh, these are you guys.

11:14.542 --> 11:17.041
Yeah. Of course we did.
Trickle-down economics.

11:17.125 --> 11:19.500
Making the rich richer
and the poor poorer since...

11:19.583 --> 11:20.875
-Forever.
-Forever.

11:20.959 --> 11:22.125
That's cute.

11:23.875 --> 11:26.208
Hanauer:
I wrote this piece for  Politio
a couple of years ago

11:26.291 --> 11:29.000
called "The Pitchforks
Are Coming for Us
Plutocrats."

11:29.083 --> 11:32.500
You know, just offered
the basic argument,
which is that if any society

11:32.583 --> 11:34.375
which becomes
radically unequal,

11:34.458 --> 11:37.834
either it becomes
a police state,
or devolves into revolution.

11:37.917 --> 11:40.083
There aren't any
counter-examples to that,

11:40.166 --> 11:44.709
-and that we should
try to avoid that.
-Yeah.

11:44.792 --> 11:47.250
I don't know.
Maybe there's plan B.

11:47.333 --> 11:50.041
In 1980, the top
one percent
of Americans

11:50.125 --> 11:52.542
got about eight
percent share
of national income,

11:52.625 --> 11:57.166
and the bottom
50 percent of Americans
got 17.7 percent.

11:57.250 --> 11:59.917
Fast-forward it
to, like, 2007.

12:00.291 --> 12:03.333
Top one percent had gone
to almost 23 percent,

12:03.417 --> 12:05.083
while the bottom
50 percent

12:05.166 --> 12:07.166
had fallen from
17 to, like, 11.

12:07.250 --> 12:10.125
-Morton: Wow.
-Hanauer: All you have to do
is take that trend,

12:10.208 --> 12:12.834
just imagine it goes
for another 20 or 30 years.

12:12.917 --> 12:17.625
That arrangement does not
resemble what we currently have.

12:17.709 --> 12:20.333
Democracy is gone,
the normal economy is gone.

12:20.417 --> 12:23.667
You're living
in some sort of weird,
feudalist hell-scape.

12:23.750 --> 12:27.750
It's hard to believe that we're
going to be able to get
the country back on track

12:27.834 --> 12:30.458
without some pretty crazy
stuff going down.

12:30.542 --> 12:32.750
Crazy in what sense?
What do you see
as happening?

12:32.834 --> 12:35.625
I mean, I think
that you're gonna see
a ton of social unrest

12:35.709 --> 12:38.375
play out over the next
ten, ten to 20 years.

12:38.458 --> 12:41.500
Do people still have contingency
plans? I remember around
the time of the WTO,

12:41.583 --> 12:44.959
there was a lot of talk
about, like, you know,
like, Batman tunnels.

12:45.041 --> 12:47.917
and stuff like that
through the city.
Are people...?

12:48.000 --> 12:49.750
-Oh, yeah.
-Morton: Yeah?

12:49.834 --> 12:52.333
Yes. Yeah.

12:52.417 --> 12:54.750
Everybody, like, in my world,
everybody's like,

12:54.834 --> 12:56.625
"Where are we gonna go?"

12:56.709 --> 12:59.625
♪ ♪

13:03.750 --> 13:06.083
Morton:
The Raven Ridge Survival Condo
was originally constructed

13:06.166 --> 13:09.166
as in intercontinental
ballistic missile silo
in the '60s.

13:09.625 --> 13:13.083
After its ICBM was taken out,
the silo sat derelict
for 40 years,

13:13.166 --> 13:15.792
until developer Larry Hall
bought it to make into
a data center

13:15.875 --> 13:18.583
that could withstand
the shockwave
from a nuclear explosion.

13:18.667 --> 13:21.959
Then he had a change of heart,
and decided to convert
his plans for a server farm

13:22.041 --> 13:24.709
into a shelter for the most
precious data of all:

13:24.792 --> 13:26.667
human civilization.

13:26.750 --> 13:28.625
-Morton: Hi.
-Larry Hall: Thomas.

13:28.709 --> 13:30.000
-Morton: Hello.
-Larry Hall.

13:30.083 --> 13:31.959
Welcome to the Survival Condo.

13:32.041 --> 13:34.583
♪ ♪

13:37.834 --> 13:39.542
Morton:
Full-floor condo units
at Raven's Ridge

13:39.625 --> 13:42.041
start at 2.5 million dollars,
for which you get not only

13:42.125 --> 13:46.000
unlimited food, water,
electricity, and breathable,
non-radioactive air,

13:46.083 --> 13:50.125
but as many creative comforts
as you can fit into a 15-story
hole in the ground.

13:50.208 --> 13:54.000
This is the dome,
then, you have
the mechanical level,

13:54.083 --> 13:57.625
medical, security level.
This is the dental chair.

13:57.709 --> 14:01.250
And then this is the exam room.
We've got all these things
set up.

14:01.333 --> 14:04.041
Store level
with hydroponics
and aquaculture.

14:04.125 --> 14:07.667
We'll have tomatoes and lettuce
and kale, and...

14:07.750 --> 14:11.583
We also have music in here
'cause plants respond
to classical music.

14:11.667 --> 14:15.959
Then the residential levels are
five, six, seven, eight, nine,
10, and 11.

14:16.041 --> 14:20.166
It's about 940 square feet
of living space in here.

14:20.250 --> 14:22.250
